From: &quot;David Plass&quot; &lt;dplass@...&gt;
&gt; Actually this makes me think. I always bristle at the verbosity of this
&gt; pattern:
&gt;
&gt;      private SomeClass thingBeingTested = null;
&gt;
&gt; public void setUp() {
&gt;     thingBeingTested = new ThingBeingTested();
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; public void tearDown() {
&gt;     thingBeingTested = null;
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; What is the advantage of the above code over the below code:
&gt;
&gt;     private SomeClass thingBeingTested = new ThingBeingTested();
&gt;
setUp is called when that test is run. All the TestCase class instances are
constructed when the suite is created so if you have 20 test methods, you
will end up with 20 instances of ThingBeingTested existing concurrently
which could be a problem if ThingBeingTested uses some valuable resource.

&gt; In other words, do we EVER really need &#39;tearDown&#39;?  I do see the need for
&gt; setUp, especially if you need to construct (horror) interlinked mock
&gt; objects.  But why bother &#39;nulling&#39; out your locals? They&#39;ll be GC&#39;ed
anyway,
&gt; right?
&gt;
tearDown is analagous to finalize. You probably only need to use it to
release some non memory resource e.g. close a connection, rollback a
transaction., delete some temporary files

- Neil Swingler
